description.p:
Each Fund reserves the absolute right to reject a purchase order transmitted to it by the Distributor. By way of example, and not limitation, a Fund will reject a purchase order if:



    

the order is not in proper form;

the investor(s), upon obtaining the VIPER Shares ordered, would own 80% or more of the total combined voting power of all classes of stock issued by the Fund;

the Deposit Securities delivered are not as disseminated through the facilities of the AMEX for that date by the Custodian, as described above;

acceptance of the Deposit Securities would have certain adverse tax consequences to the Fund;

acceptance of the Fund Deposit would, in the opinion of counsel, be unlawful;

acceptance of the Fund Deposit would otherwise, in the discretion of the Fund or Vanguard, have an adverse effect on the Fund or any of its shareholders; or

circumstances outside the control of the Fund, the Transfer Agent, the Custodian, the Distributor, and Vanguard make it for all practical purposes impossible to process the order. Examples of such circumstances include acts of God; public service or utility problems such as fires, floods, extreme weather conditions, and power outages resulting in telephone, telecopy, and computer failures; market conditions or activities causing trading halts; systems failures involving computer or other information systems affecting the Trust, Vanguard, the Distributor, DTC, NSCC, or any other participant in the purchase process, and similar extraordinary events.

claim.claim-text:
6. A method comprising:
(a) issuing, by a first processor, a first class of shares, wherein shares of the first class of shares are bought from and redeemed with a single investment company by one or more shareholders at a net asset value;
(b) maintaining account data in one or more computers at the single investment company representative of the number of shares of the first class of shares held by each of the one or more shareholders;
(c) sending, by a first computer, data representing a basket of securities that has an equivalent monetary value to a predetermined number of shares of a second class of shares issued by the single investment company,
wherein the predetermined number of shares of the second class of shares comprises a Creation Unit, and wherein shares of the second class of shares are listed for trading on a national securities exchange, and wherein shares of the second class of shares are bought and sold by one or more investors at negotiated market prices;
(d) receiving, at a second processer, the data representing the basket of securities;
(e) in response to receiving the data representing a basket of securities, issuing, by the second processor the predetermined number of shares of the second class of shares;
(f) sending to the first computer, data representing the predetermined number of shares of the second class of shares;
(g) entering, at a second computer, an order to purchase or sell a number of shares of the predetermined number of the second class of shares on behalf of a first investor;
(h) executing the order to purchase or sell the number of shares entered in step (g), wherein executing the order comprises:
(i) generating data representing the purchase or sell order of the number of shares by the second computer on behalf of the first investor,
(ii) communicating the data representing the purchase or sell order of the number of shares to a third computer on behalf of the first investor, and
(iii) fulfilling the purchase or sell order by automatically buying or selling the number of shares at publically quoted prices by the third computer;

(i) updating account data of the first investor in the second computer to reflect a new number of shares of the second class of shares held by the first investor; and
(j) maintaining data in the one or more computers at the single investment company of the total number of outstanding shares of the first class of shares and the second class of shares, wherein an owner of any share of the first class of shares and the second class of shares has an undivided interest in the single investment company.
